The primary advantage over just adding traits is that this guarantees a consistent API and prevents people from having to implement and re-implement the functionality of `get` and `get_ref`.

Basically:

``` rust
struct Request {
  body: String
  extensions: AnyMap
}

impl Extensible for Request { etc. }

// Stupid example.
struct BodyLength { len: uint }

// Implementation is much simpler, you only deal with construction.
impl PluginFor<Request> for BodyLength {
  fn construct(req: &Request) -> BodyLength {
    BodyLength { len: req.len() }
  }
}

// Usage site
// Safe, namespaced, typesafe, guaranteed interface
let body_length = req.get::<BodyLength>();

// Middleware alternative:

struct BodyLength { len: uint };

impl Middleware for BodyLength {
  fn enter(req: &Request) -> Result<(), Box<Show>> {
    req.extensions.insert(BodyLength { req.len() });
    Ok(());
  }
}

trait BodyLength { fn body_length(&self) -> uint }

impl BodyLength for Request {
  fn body_length(&self) -> uint {
    self.extensions.find::<BodyLength>().unwrap().len
  }
}

// Insert into server in the correct order! (error prone/not-safe)
server.whatever(BodyLength)

// Usage site 
// Additional problem here is that there's no requirement to expose & and an &mut vs.
// by value etc. Every middleware has its own naming convention and methods easily
// will clash name-spaces.
let body_length = req.body_length()
```

This does not obsolete the need for Mixins as an approach - templating still needs `Response::render` but it removes the need to duplicate this basic API - this is very nice for a large variety of things and can still be used internally by Mixins which expose other things. The major idea is it is automatically correctly lazy, correctly order-independent, and correctly matching with best style.

